%[text] %[text:anchor:T_0B83894C] # Design LLC Resonant Converter
%[text] This design solution demonstrates how to design and analyze the performance of an LLC resonant DC-DC converter. The LLC resonant converter is a soft-switching topology that achieves turn-on zero-voltage switching (ZVS) for the primary MOSFETs and zero-current switching (ZCS) for the secondary diodes. This topology enables high power density, reduced switching losses, and lower electromagnetic interference (EMI). Recent advancements in semiconductor technology and high-power materials allow for higher switching frequencies which reduces the size of magnetic components. Soft-switching operation further decreases switching losses and enhances efficiency.
%[text] This design solution shows how to estimate and adjust the resonant tank parameters to meet specific design requirements and optimize converter performance. The workflow demonstrates how to use time-domain simulation of sinusoidal disturbances to extract the system frequency response. This approach enables extraction of accurate linearized plant models that you can use to controller tuning.
%[text:tableOfContents]{"heading":"Table of Contents"}
%%
%[text] %[text:anchor:H_A6556DB6] ## Design Solution Scope
%[text] This design solution outlines the steps required to translate converter design specifications into a validated design. The workflow uses the first harmonic approximation (FHA) to estimate the resonant tank parameters. You can plot the gain curve for various load resistances, quality factors, and the ratio of magnetizing inductance to series resonant inductance. The solution also provides guidance on linearizing the converter and tuning the controller. Additionally, it summarizes the switching and conduction losses for each semiconductor device and estimates the overall efficiency of the converter.
%[text] In this design solution, you:
%[text] - Estimate resonant tank parameters
%[text] - Plot the gain curve using the FHA
%[text] - Tune resonant tank parameters
%[text] - Linearize the plant and tune the controller
%[text] - Estimate power loss and efficiency \
%[text] %[text:anchor:H_B6482FCD] ## System Overview
%[text] The LLC resonant full-bridge DC-DC converter model includes four key components:
%[text] - Full-bridge inverter with SiC MOSFET devices
%[text] - Resonant tank comprising a capacitor and a transformer with specified leakage and magnetizing inductance
%[text] - Full-bridge diode rectifier
%[text] - LLC controller  \
%[text] This figure shows a top-level schematic of the LLC converter. The converter utilizes the transformer leakage inductance to achieve resonance and employs a full bridge diode rectifier on the secondary side.
%[text] Open the model 
  %[control:button:6d7c]{"position":[1,2]}
modelName = "LLCResonantConverterFullBridge";
open_system(modelName);
%[text] ![](text:image:437c)
%%
%[text] %[text:anchor:H_72e5] ## Select LLC Resonant Tank Parameters
%[text] To design and tune the LLC converter, use the `EstimateLLCResonantConvertersParameters` live code. In this workflow, you specify your design requirements and configure the resonant tank. The live code plots the gain curve of the resonant tank using the FHA method.
%[text] To open the LLC resonant converter design workflow, run the following command in the MATLAB® Command Window:
%[text] ```matlabCodeExample
%[text] edit 'EstimateLLCConverterResonantTankParameters'
%[text] ```
if ~exist('LLCDesign', 'var');LLCConverterDefaultInputParameters; end
disp(table(designTable,'VariableNames',"LLC Converter Estimated Design Parameters")); %[output:53a685d5]
%[text] ## Select Converter Components and Controller
%[text] This design solution assists you in selecting appropriate ratings for the primary MOSFET and secondary diode. The workflow provides steps for tuning the controller parameters. It also linearizes the LLC converter plant by estimating the plant poles and zeros using time-domain simulation-based frequency response analysis. This method injects sinestream disturbances into the system and analyzes the time-domain response to accurately characterize the plant dynamics.
%[text] To open the LLC converter component selection workflow, run the following command in the MATLAB Command Window:
%[text] ```matlabCodeExample
%[text] edit 'SelectLLCConverterComponents'
%[text] ```
%%
%[text] ## LLC Resonant Converter Circuit
%[text] The LLC resonant converter plant consists of three main components: the primary full-bridge inverter with MOSFETs, the resonant tank, and the secondary diode bridge rectifier. You can choose between two levels of model fidelity for the MOSFETs and diodes. For faster simulation performance during controller tuning, use the Simscape™ Electrical™ MOSFET (Ideal, Switching) component with the thermal port disabled. Similarly, use the Diode block from the Simscape Foundation Library. To estimate switching losses and efficiency, enable the thermal port for the primary MOSFET devices. For improved diode loss prediction, select the tabulated I-V curve option.
%[text] To open the LLC resonant converter circuit subsystem, at the MATLAB Command Window, run:
%[text] ```matlabCodeExample
%[text] open_system(strcat(modelName,"/LLC Converter Power Circuit"));
%[text] ```
%[text] ![](text:image:64d8)
%[text] 
%[text] ## Plot Simulation Results
%[text] You can simulate the LLC resonant converter under various reference voltage and load conditions. Analyze the resulting current and voltage waveforms, and plot the loss curves to evaluate converter performance.
%%
%[text] ### Set up Simulation
%[text] This section guides you in setting the model fidelity for the primary MOSFET and secondary diode. Specify the operating conditions, including output load power, input voltage, and reference output voltage.
  %[control:button:4fef]{"position":[1,2]}
voltageReference = simscape.Value(360,"V");  % Output reference voltage (V)
inputDCVoltage   = simscape.Value(380,"V");  % Input DC voltage (V)
outputLoadPower  = simscape.Value(7000,"W"); % DC output power (W)
simulationTime   = simscape.Value(0.015,"s"); % Simulation time (s)
% Set simulation time to ensure that the output voltage reaches steady state.

% Configure model
primaryMOSFETBlock =  "MOSFET (Ideal, Switching) without Thermal";
secondaryDiodeBlock = "Ideal Diode";

% Set the parameters into the model
simIn = setupLLCConverterModel(modelName,MOSFETModel=primaryMOSFETBlock, DiodeModel=secondaryDiodeBlock,...
    Vref=voltageReference,Pload=outputLoadPower, Vin=inputDCVoltage,SimTime=simulationTime);
%[text] ### Plot LLC Converter Voltage and Current
%[text] Plot the inverter output voltage, transformer secondary voltage, transformer currents, and input and output DC currents of the LLC resonant converter for the given load and reference voltage conditions.
simOut = sim(simIn); % Simulate the model
llcSimulationData = plotLLCResonantTankVoltageCurrent(simOut.logsoutLLCConverter, ResonantFrequency=LLCSpec.resonantFrequency); %[output:21968d0f]
%%
%[text] ### Estimate Power Loss and Efficiency
%[text] To assess LLC converter power losses and efficiency, you need to use a model configuration that exposes the thermal port of the MOSFET (Ideal, Switching) and Diode blocks. This configuration adds tabulated switching losses and on-state conduction losses based on tabulated I-V curves.
  %[control:button:55d7]{"position":[1,2]}
modelName = "LLCResonantConverterFullBridge";
voltageReference = simscape.Value(360,"V");   % Reference voltage (V)
inputDCVoltage   = simscape.Value(380,"V");   % Input DC voltage (V)
outputLoadPower  = simscape.Value(7000,"W");  % DC output power (W)
simulationTime   = simscape.Value(0.01,"s");  % Simulation time (s)
% Set simulation time to ensure that the output voltage reaches steady state.
%[text] The LLC resonant converter is a soft-switching topology that achieves low switching losses by providing zero-voltage switching (ZVS) in the primary MOSFETs and zero-current switching (ZCS) in the secondary diodes over most load and voltage ranges. You can categorize power losses in the converter into three components: inverter MOSFET losses, rectifier diode losses, and losses in passive components such as transformer winding resistance.
lossData = getLLCPowerLossCharacteristics(modelName,Vref=voltageReference,Pload=outputLoadPower,Vin=inputDCVoltage,SimTime=simulationTime); %[output:96e49c16] %[output:73152447] %[output:0178ec74]
%%
%[text] %[text:anchor:H_7A3E9C04] ## Conclusion
%[text] This live code, supporting scripts and models has shown how MATLAB® scripting and Simscape Electrical can be used to design an LLC resonant full-bridge converter. Steps covered include sizing of the key passive components to meet converter requirements, modeling the circuit at lower fidelity to support fast simulation and control design, and modeling the circuit with sufficient detail to predict losses and efficiency. For further information on LLC resonant converter design, please consult the list of referenced papers.
%[text] %[text:anchor:H_73eb] ## References
%[text] 1. Sam Abdel-Rahman, "Resonant LLC Converter:Operation and Design 250W, 33Vin, 400Vout, Design Example", Infineon Technologies North America (IFNA) Corp.
%[text] 2. P. P. Gupta, N. Kumar and U. Nangia, "Design and Analysis of LLC Resonant Converter and CCCV Topology for Battery Charging," *2022 2nd Asian Conference on Innovation in Technology (ASIANCON)*, Ravet, India, 2022, pp. 1-5, doi: 10.1109/ ASIANCON55314.2022.9909135.
%[text] 3. Christophe Basso, "Control Methods of LLC Converters", Future Electronics, 12th Power Analysis and Design Symposium.
%[text] 4. B. Li, X. Zhang, D. Zhou, S. Sun, Y. Wang and D. Xu, "Soft-switching Characteristics Analysis Based on LLC Resonant Converter," *2018 IEEE Transportation Electrification Conference and Expo, Asia-Pacific (ITEC Asia-Pacific)*, Bangkok, Thailand, 2018, pp. 1-6, doi: 10.1109/ITEC-AP.2018.8433301.
%[text] 5. Dhaval Patel and Ramesh Kankanala, "Digital Compensator Design for LLC Resonant Converter", Application note (AN1477), Microchip Technology Inc. \
